creator: ivelin@apache.org
text:
We are running Apache 2.0.43 with SSL, mod_proxy and mod_rewrite rules on 
Win2K.
Under moderate load (about 10 requests per second), apache behaves well for 
hours. There are no memory leaks. 
After 5-6 hours ot suddenly pegs the CPU to 100% and stops serving pages.
At the time of the problem, the error log shows that the max threads count has 
been exceeded and apache will restart its child process. 
Apparently the restart doesn't succeed, because the servers stops responding.
It does not crash with an error message. The error log does not suggest 
further problems also.
This scenario is reproducable on 2 independent servers over a period of a week.
There are no signs for external attmept for attack in the log files around the 
time of the hang.

creator: ivelin@apache.org

creator: ivelin@apache.org

text:
Unfortunately this cannot be a duplicate of 13661, because
both web servers are running on static IPs behind a load balancer.

Here are the latest information from our operations team:

Unfortunately stopping all AntiVirus services did not help.

Here is additionaly analisys from one of our team members:

Symptoms:
	CPU goes from a normal load to 100% and stays there.  Usually the 
system stops responding to requests.  Apache stops logging events, sometimes 
after logging an Out of Threads message to the error.log, sometimes not.  
Process lists indicate that Apache is taking up all CPU resources.  Process 
monitoring indicates that the actual child process is taking the CPU.  If the 
log contains an Out of Threads message, usually the second web server will go 
down with the same symptoms within 15 minutes or so.  If there is no OOT 
message, usually this will not happen.

Info:
	Memory seems steady.  I/O seems OK as well.  No pattern in when these 
occur.  Slightly more likely during the week then the weekend.  HTML requests 
right before this happens are normal requests.  The service will rarely 
respond 
to NET STOP commands when in this state.  Reboots correct this problem.  Anti-
Virus has been stopped on the system.  After stopping AV on 11-12, the problem 
happened several hours later, then not again until 11-18, the longest period 
yet.  Since then, the Patrol has reported 8 various CPU pegs, including the 
first one on 11-18.  The Web boxes are Win2K SP2.  Apache is 2.0.42.  We are 
not able to duplicate this problem in the lab under stress conditions.

Speculation:
	I believe this may be two linked but still separate problems, one, the 
OOT problem, the other, the "stoplog" problem.  I say this because with an 
OOT, 
if threads are not released, Apache will not accept connections, and there's 
nothing to put in the logs.  Also, this issue somehow crosses to the other 
web, 
which soon goes down.  On the other hand, the stoplog problem never crosses to 
another server, and often the server continues to serve requests after the CPU 
peg.  These requests are not logged, however.  I also believe this to be a non-
RSM related problem as I feel we would be seeing more regular occurrences or 
duplication in the lab.  Possibly a malformed HTML request.

Conclusion:
	Stopping AV did not fix this problem. 

Thanks,
Andrew
creator: ivelin@apache.org

text:
Please see bug # 10266 which I just reopened and I highly suspect is the same 
problem as being reported by this bug.
creator: dcook@cookware.com
wrowe@apache.org
text:
Quick comment, it's highly unlikely that bug 12066 is related, this is
  down in the MPM layer, and those are entirely different between Unix and
  Win32.

  I suspect the network stack still.  Stopping network AntiVirus or Firewall
  drivers WILL NOT CLEAR UP THE PROBLEM.  They remain loaded, even if they
  are nonfunctioning, their disfunctional behavior remains.

  Please try disabling AV and Firewall, then restarting the machine with those
  products altogether disabled.  Confirm they did not start.  Then see if the
  problem can be reproduced.

creator: ivelin@apache.org
text:
We reinstalled Apache on Clean Windows boxes.
AV was never installed on these new boxes.
Same problem.

The child is clearly determined that a fatal condition occurred in trying
  to AcceptEx on the connection, as the error WSAEHOSTDOWN indicates.

  The parent process needed to recognize the condition, invalidate all of
  the now-invalid listeners and restart them.  Unfortunately the parent
  process isn't terribly clever about doing so.

  We will look at this report and attempt to come up with a fix.  You can
  rest assured that this has something to do with your network/dhcp or other
  issue, and not with network drivers such as antivirus or firewall.

  Please, never again post so much cruft into the 'additional comments' block,
  this report is impossible to follow.  That's what 'Create new attachment'
  is for.
creator: wrowe@apache.org

text:
We also think that the problem is not related to AV or firewall.
I accept the criticism about the log dump. 
Should have created an attachment.
creator: ivelin@apache.org

text:
Are you using DHCP and changing dynamic addresses, as I'm guessing?
  Do you have DNS server stability issues?
creator: wrowe@apache.org
ivelin@apache.org
text:
We switched to Apache 2.0.43 over a week ago and the problem never appeared.
As far as we are concerned, you can consider the bug closed.
